I am comparing my own Cartesian impedance controller derivation against this repo. Please do a careful check, not a hand-wavy one.

My version is this.

I want the task-space impedance
M_m(\ddot r-\ddot r_d) + D_m(\dot r-\dot r_d) + K_m(r-r_d) = F_r

From that I define the commanded task acceleration
a_cmd = \ddot r_d + M_m^{-1}[D_m(\dot r_d-\dot r) + K_m(r_d-r) + F_r]

Then I use task-space inverse dynamics
M_r(q)\ddot r + S_r(q,\dot q)\dot r + g_r(q) = J_r^{-T}(q)u + F_r

and choose torque
u = J_r^T(q)[M_r(q)a_cmd + S_r(q,\dot q)\dot r + g_r(q) - F_r]

Equivalently, if expanded:
u = J_r^T(q)[
M_r(q)\ddot r_d
+ M_r(q)M_m^{-1}(D_m(\dot r_d-\dot r) + K_m(r_d-r))
+ S_r(q,\dot q)\dot r
+ g_r(q)
+ (M_r(q)M_m^{-1} - I)F_r
]

What I think I am doing is:
1. choose desired impedance
2. solve it for a_cmd
3. choose u so that the closed-loop robot satisfies \ddot r = a_cmd
4. therefore the robot realizes the desired impedance

